description.text:
Photos 2-6 show an actual CNC-milled tooling board foam using a 1/32" drill bit. It was 2/3 the size of the original. For download here, this is the same STL file that was used.

Inspired by Cosmo Wenman, who recently wrote the following on Medium:

"It’s an inversion of the goal of creating access to a physical space. It’s taking a collection and projecting it outward so that people outside the museum can access the designs directly, wherever they happen to be.

What I’m advocating is not anticipating particular installations, particular uses, or particular audiences. It’s dumping the data online so that the users outside the museum can use it in ways that we could never anticipate or plan for."

This object satisfies a broad range of interests: 16th century calligraphic ornaments, stone-etching, black-letter typography, elaborate ligatures, the history and use of almanacs, fine art as domestic and portable objects, and German culture from the Late Baroque era.

It is closely related to manuscript scribes who wrote with ink on vellum. This technique seems to have been developed 500 years ago to write beautifully in stone! As far as I know, everything on the stone was hand-written with a special medium, and then an acid bath brought the negative space down just a few millimeters, creating a subtle relief with some lines as thin as a hair. In German the technique is called Steinätzung, or stone-etching.

Creator: Johannes Helsspect Ratisponensis F. (John Helsspect of Regensburg created this)
Date: 1599
Dimensions: 11.5 x 17.5 x 0.75 inches
Weight: ~ 24 lbs
Material: Solnhofen limestone
Date Acquired: 2014-09-06
From Where?: Bobingen, Germany (180 miles west of Regensburg)

A damaged pocket-size version can be found in the British Museum. His famous contemporary is Andreas Pleninger [1555-1607].

A very special thanks to Sean O'Reilly and 3D Printsmith LLC for making this all possible. He used a calibrated structured light scanner and mapped numerous close-up shots to a macro view of the stone.

Thank you all for downloading! I hope you enjoy it and look at it closely, it really rewards you with a wealth of detail the more you study it!

Stephen Chow
chowcollection.culturalspot.org

P.S. Let me know if you print this! I'd love to see the results. My e-mail is: [email protected]

I created this to pimp up my robotic lawn mower (Husqvarna Automower 310) but the design is not limited to robotic lawn mowers by any means. The spoiler can be mounted anywhere, you can scale it up or down to fit your needs! See pictures for a x4 down scaled version. The model was made in Rhino and the original file is included, feel free to modify it!

74x291x63mm

To be able to print this large I had to split the wing in two parts, each 150mm long. It's best printed standing so you need 150mm space in your printer or scale it down.

Notes:

Lower layer height will make it easier to sand paper and paint afterwards if you want. If your printer support Skirt/Brim I would suggest you to add that as 2 first layers, 0.2mm from part and 8 outlines when printing the wing. That will make it much more stable and help adhesion. If you print the wing without caps/fins and support (Wing_split_A_simple.stl or Wing_complete_noCaps.stl) I can recommend "corkscrew/vase mode" which gives very nice result. Assembling
  1. The two wing parts has to be glued together for a strong bond (you may have to fine tune the support beneath the wing using a small file)
  2. Optional: Sand paper and paint the wing and legs for a nice finish!
  3. Mount the legs where you want them using glue or tape
  4. Mount the spoiler on your product using screws, glue or tape

If you print the whole wing standing you need to mount the top fin/cap afterwards.

  1. Used a picture of a real spoiler and designed the corresponding wing profiles

  3. Designed the legs, fins and support

Recently I had to cut an methacrylate circle of a certain diameter and I had no compass or similar tool to draw the circle. Looked here for a design that meet my needs but couldn't find any. I like simple and functional things and I remembered some tool my drawing teacher used when I was a child... that came to my mind. Not a joke!! This works for me better than any toy. My hands handle this well, not like some toys that always break in my hands. I needed something that I could attach several kind of tools, to draw, to mark, to pinch, etc. Don't make mistake, there are awesome compass designs out there, but as always I wanted my own design to be able to change it. I believe in the open source hardware so there are the FreeCAD sources. So I had to begin a little project to design this manual drafting compass. I call it the poor man's compass because it is simple to print, simple to mount, and simple to use, but also sturdy and durable. Printing requires no support. Use an M4 hex bolt, a washer or two, and a M4 wingnut to join the two parts. Use some rubber bands to fix your favourite tools to the wings of the compass, done. Once more an simple design for a simple thing.

description.text:
This is a collar that lets you insert a 0.2 mL PCR tube into a 1.5 mL tube. A set of 24 pieces prints in about 1.5 hours (60 mm/s, 0.40 mm nozzle).

The collar's low profile lets me fit PCR tubes into machines like tissue lysers — extremely convenient grinder-to-thermocycler workflow! You can also centrifuge PCR tubes in a larger machine now.

You should test your own tubes and prints to make sure that they can withstand centrifugation at the forces, periods, and temperatures you need, before you risk samples. This collar cannot help you if you use weak, low-quality tubes!

The collars are a secure press-fit into 1.5 mL tubes that have an inner diameter of 9.00 mm. Cut the lids off your 1.5 mL tubes to make them easier to handle.

If the fit of your smaller tubes is too tight, you can expand the openings using a knife-edge reamer tool.

Jun 15 2016: Initial release.

Apr 18 2017: Replaced the design with a new one that uses less material, prints faster, and fits inside a 1.5 mL centrifuge tube. A friend of mine had the old design delaminate along the print layers while she was centrifuging something. By relying on the support of the 1.5 mL tube, I hope to prevent this from happening to anyone else.

May 7 2017: Tapered the top of the adapter into a flat dome. This makes it easier to uncap and remove tubes.

Marlin Firmware uploaded! Z-probe offset may need to be adjusted in the configuration.h file.

The air diverter needs to be glued to the fan holder near the nozzle otherwise this fan will cool an actively heating nozzle by 50C and trip the thermal runaway settings. I also wrap my nozzle in pot holder insulation and at 100% fan speed the nozzle doesn't cool down at all.

description.text: The Chinese New Year is almost here, and we are entering the Year of the Dragon.  Celebrate the New Year with these fun chinese dragon coins and medallions. Give them out as party favors, play games with them, or just have the coolest medallion at the party.

Download. Resize if you want. Print. Post a pic of you wearing the medallion! This is my first real attempt at doing something intricate with Blender. I'm happy with the results. I lost the fine details when I printed the coin on my ToM, but you still get the general idea of the design. I'm including the .blend file for everyone to play with. I did not design the dragon. I'm not that good. I used the following image from the wikimedia commons: http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Dragon_from_Chinese_Dragon_Banner_Red_Version.svg by Tsange. Even though it's public domain, I like to give credit where credit is due.

description.text: While playing with my Moon Rover tread, I found it zipped into itself pretty well.  This is an adjusted version that can zip into both sides.  It's flexible in several dimensions and easily layered.  It's quite fun, and I'm curious what uses or interesting shapes you all can come up with for it.

I can't get Skeinforge to skein zipper.stl, so I'd recommend printing zipperSolid.stl with fill turned off, so it just prints the perimeter.  That'll make two zippers, which you can cut apart with scissors.  Cut the loops off so they look like zipper.stl; that'll allow them to hook into each other end to end as well as side to side.  
The OpenSCAD file is fully parametric; only four parameters define the shape and they're all up front in the code.  It's set for a thread thickness of 0.42mm, which the TOM MK6 default for 0.3mm layer hieght.  Just read the thickness out of RepG and put that value into the scad file.

title: InMoov Neo Pixel Ring Arc Reactor Logo

description.text: Since the InMoov DiskInternV3.stl logo plate that mounts inside the four DiskExternV2.stl did not print well or have good contrast I decided to print the InMoov logo on Transparency Film, and mount that over a smooth plate, with an outer mounting ring to hold it all in place. I used flat black paint on the DiskExternV2.stl assembly and the mounting ring. The gold rings are 23 karat gold leaf and make this look like a Mayan artifact! I'm driving the Arduino Nano with this InMoovLogo.txt script. (rename it to .ino) Install the Arduino Library Neo Pixel support. I'm on a Mac so I did first install the FTDI driver, which got the usbserial showing up in the system report. Then I had to install the Mac serial driver here http://0xcf.com/2015/03/13/chinese-arduinos-with-ch340-ch341-serial-usb-chip-on-os-x-yosemite/ (I apparently have $3 Nano knock offs from China) - and they're working just fine.

description.text:
This drier allows you to keep all your Hurom vertical juicer parts to dry in a minimum footprint.

Some top-notch Hurom models (HH2) come with something similar, but it is not available for earlier models like 600 or 700. I do own one 600 series and I wanted to have something similar, so I grab FreeCAD and made it.

It works fine for a Hurom 600, should work fine for a 700 and maybe for the HH2. It may also work for the Omega branded juicer that seems to be a clone of the Hurom.

There are several files:

  • One single piece model for those with a very big printer (it requires something like 25 cm in Z axis). One solid version and one wedge hollowed version.
  • Three pieces, parts 1, 2 and 3, with a M8 plastic made threads (use a M8 nut and screw or better threading tools to clean the threads in the plastic before attaching the parts together).
  • Full FreeCAD source (Part Design NEXT, use the daily version of FreeCAD, older versions will not open it right).

Tip: In case you broke the thread between part 1 and part 2, you may want to make a thru hole in part1 and put a M8 bolt from beneath to attach it directly to part2.

Enjoy!

description.text:
My son wanted foot pegs for his BMX.

The correct diameter to be fitted on the wheel axle wasn't avalaible at the shop.
So i designed it.
And printed it with polycarbonate (color is flashy....)

There are 2 sizes:
13mm center hole to fit the rear axle.
8.9mm center hole to fit the front axle.

I didn't design any threads, as the axle threads are very very fine, so i'm sure it wouldn't have printed correctly.
So you have to "force" the peg into the axle, thus creating the thread like with a tap.(put some grease to help)
You need 2 of each obviously.

I did 3 processes in Simplify:
-For the first 20mm in height : infill at 100% and 10 perimeters , to create a very strong shell around the axle of the Wheel)
-Then from 20 to 100 mm, 70% infill,10 perimeters
-finally above 100mm, for the nut, 100% infill,10 perimeters

It seems to be strong as i can jump on the pegs (63 kg)

No supports while printing but a good raft (2 layers) with the polycarbonate to avoid systematic warping.

description.text: Introducing a fully printable flying object: the Whirligig. Just like its wooden toy ancestor, the whirligig will fly like a helicopter several meters when spun by hand. Here's a video of the Whirligig in action: http://youtu.be/Ly2nxN80kGs No glue required! Just snap it together and let it fly!

Print all parts. I highly recommend printing the wings without a raft if you can stand it so that the surfaces are nice and smooth. Definitely print the other tall, slender parts with a raft for stability.
Snap one wing into each hole on Base1 by gently squeezing the tabs on each wing together and firmly pushing them through the hole until they snap into place. Put them on opposite sides, build platform side down. The fit should be snug. Be careful; the tabs on the wings can break off if twisted too hard.
Connect the shaft of Base1 to the shaft of Base2 with the Connector. The added length provides stability during flight.
To operate, spin between your hands counter clockwise and let go! Enjoy!
